    "\n",
    "To distinguish between **regime-driven variation** and **true fault-related changes**, sensor distributions were analyzed across the two operating regimes: **A** and **B**.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "#### 1. Clear Regime Separation in Core Process Variables\n",
    "\n",
    "Several key variables show strong shifts between regimes:\n",
    "\n",
    "**Reactor Temperature**\n",
    "- Regime A → centered around **~181–182°C**\n",
    "- Regime B → centered around **~194–195°C**\n",
    "\n",
    "**Reactor Pressure**\n",
    "- Regime A → **~15.6–15.8 bar**\n",
    "- Regime B → **~17.4–17.7 bar**\n",
    "\n",
    "This indicates:\n",
    "> The two regimes operate at fundamentally different thermodynamic conditions.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Implication:**\n",
    "- A single global threshold would be misleading\n",
    "- Models must be **regime-aware**\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "#### 2. Performance Metrics Shift with Regime\n",
    "\n",
    "**Conversion Rate**\n",
    "- Slightly higher in **Regime B**\n",
    "- More variability (longer lower tail)\n",
    "\n",
    "**Yield**\n",
    "- Regime B → higher average (~82.2–82.4)\n",
    "- Regime A → slightly lower (~81.6–81.9)\n",
    "\n",
    "This suggests:\n",
    "> Regime B may represent a **higher-performance operating mode**\n",
    "\n",
    "**Implication:**\n",
    "- Performance metrics must be interpreted **relative to regime**\n",
    "- Important for optimization and benchmarking\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "#### 3. Selectivity Remains Stable Across Regimes\n",
    "\n",
    "- Very similar distributions in A and B\n",
    "- Only minor differences in spread\n",
    "\n",
    "This indicates:\n",
    "> Selectivity is relatively insensitive to regime changes.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Implication:**\n",
    "- Acts as a **stable control variable**\n",
    "- Useful baseline metric\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "#### 4. Vibration Behavior is Consistent but Shows Extreme Outliers\n",
    "\n",
    "- Similar central distribution (~1.45–1.5)\n",
    "- Large spikes (up to ~3.5+) in both regimes\n",
    "\n",
    "This suggests:\n",
    "> Vibration anomalies are **not regime-dependent**\n",
    "\n",
    "**Implication:**\n",
    "- Strong candidate for **fault detection**\n",
    "- Outliers likely indicate **mechanical issues**\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "#### 5. Power Consumption Slightly Higher in Regime B\n",
    "\n",
    "- Small upward shift in Regime B\n",
    "- Similar spread across regimes\n",
    "\n",
    "This indicates:\n",
    "> Higher operating conditions in Regime B require more energy input.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Implication:**\n",
    "- Power reflects **process load**\n",
    "- Can be used for efficiency monitoring\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "### Key Insight: Regime ≠ Fault\n",
    "\n",
    "> Differences between Regime A and B are **normal operating behavior**, not anomalies.\n",
    "\n",
    "This is critical because:\n",
    "- Without accounting for regime, models may:\n",
    "  - misclassify normal points as faults\n",
    "  - learn incorrect patterns\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "### Modeling Implications\n",
    "\n",
    "A robust fault detection system should:\n",
    "\n",
    "#### 1. Be Regime-Aware\n",
    "- Include `operating_regime` as a feature  \n",
    "**OR**\n",
    "- Train separate models per regime\n",
    "\n",
    "#### 2. Use Regime-Normalized Features\n",
    "- Example:\n",
    "  - deviation from regime mean\n",
    "  - z-scores within each regime\n",
    "\n",
    "#### 3. Focus on Regime-Invariant Signals\n",
    "- Vibration → strong anomaly signal\n",
    "- Sudden deviations from regime baseline\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "### Final Takeaway\n",
    "\n",
    "> The system operates in two distinct, stable regimes with different baselines.\n",
    "\n",
    "Therefore:\n",
    "- Fault detection must focus on **deviations within a regime**, not differences between regimes\n",
    "\n",
    "This distinction is essential for building a **reliable and production-ready model**."
   ]
